menu "HTTP Client Reuse"

config HTTP_REUSE_ENABLE
    bool "Enable HTTP client reuse pool"
    default y
    help
        When enabled, the http_reuse component installs linker --wrap hooks for
        esp_http_client_init / esp_http_client_cleanup / esp_http_client_perform
        so that handles are kept in a pool and reused across requests targeting
        the same endpoint (matched by scheme + host + port), reducing TLS
        handshake overhead for repeated calls. On a perform failure for a
        reused connection, the wrapper transparently closes the socket and
        retries esp_http_client_perform once.

        When disabled, the wrappers forward directly to the real
        esp_http_client_init / _cleanup / _perform and no pool is maintained.

config HTTP_REUSE_MAX_POOL
    int "Maximum pooled HTTP clients"
    depends on HTTP_REUSE_ENABLE
    range 4 16
    default 4 if LWIP_MAX_SOCKETS < 8
    default 6 if LWIP_MAX_SOCKETS < 12
    default 10 if LWIP_MAX_SOCKETS < 20
    default 12 if LWIP_MAX_SOCKETS < 32
    help
        Upper bound on the number of HTTP clients kept in the pool after
        requests complete. When the pool is full, the least-recently-used
        client is closed to make room for a new one.

        Each pooled client may hold an open socket while idle. The preset
        default grows with Component config -> LWIP -> Max number of open
        sockets (LWIP_MAX_SOCKETS) so the pool leaves headroom for DNS,
        MQTT, Wi-Fi management, and other parallel TCP users. If you raise
        this option a lot, raise LWIP_MAX_SOCKETS (and heap / FD_SETSIZE per
        LWIP help) accordingly.

        Rough sizing (each concurrent long-lived HTTPS endpoint may hold one
        pooled client; actual use depends on your code paths):
        - IM stacks such as QQ or Feishu often need about 1 to 2 clients.
        - A typical web-search integration often needs about 1 client.
        - A single LLM HTTP client flow often needs about 2 clients.
        If you enable more capabilities in parallel, increase this value only
        as much as you need; each pooled client consumes TLS buffers and heap,
        so stay within available RAM.

endmenu
